The President of Senior Staff Association of Electricity Employees and Allied Companies of Nigeria (SSAEAC), Comrade Chris Okonkwo, has called on Federal Government to tackle dearth of infrastructural development. According to him, if the problem roads, rail lines and electricity supply infrastructure are solved it would alleviate the present stress faced by Nigerians , According to him, it will be the greatest democracy dividend to citizens, adding that the people are aware of government efforts in this area but regret that a lot still needs to be done. The senior staff of electricity helmsman noted that privatization of power sector is yet to achieve stated objective of expanded capacity, reliability of supply and cheap electricity. He said,’’ It was obviously badly designed and implemented hence the failure in all fronts of expectation. I am not pleased with the way and manner citizens are helping themselves in the provision of the essential service at high cost detrimental to individual or corporate entities survival. Also, it is at the detriment of the environment with attendant health implications to human or animal life. In the same vein, their senior counterparts in the power sector, Senior Staff Association of Electricity and Allied Companies (SSAEAC) have countered NUEE, saying the suspended strike was, in the first place, illegally prosecuted by the junior employee union, as conditions precedent to strike were not followed. Dwelling on the privatised PHCN and the strike embarked upon by National Union of Electricity Employees (NUEE) Okonkwo noted that SSAEAC have already written a letter to the minister of labour and employment, as well as the minister of power, a copy of which has gone to the presidency, detailing why the strike was a wrong approach. According to Okonkwo, there was the need for an urgent intervention in the power sector to save it from imminent collapse.